'''William John Adie MD Ed., FRCP''' (1886–1935) was a British physician and [[neurologist]] known for describing the [[Adie syndrome]] and [[narcolepsy]].

==Biography==
William Adie was born in [[Geelong]], Australia, on 31 October 1886. He was educated at Flinder's School, but had to leave school to support his family at the age of 13 when his father died in 1899.<ref name=whonamedit>[http://www.whonamedit.com/doctor.cfm/127.html William John Adie at Who Named It]</ref> He worked as an office errand boy, and an employer noticed his ability to learn. He funded evening classes for Adie, who was able to pass the university entrance examination. A doctor in Geelong, Dr. Arthur South, inspired him to study medicine.<ref name=whonamedit />

An uncle in Boston, Massachusetts paid £19 for a one-way ticket for Adie to travel to England to study medicine, which he did at the [[University of Edinburgh]] with the help of his uncle and a scholarship.<ref name=whonamedit /> He qualified M.B. Ch.B. in 1911.<ref name=bmj /> He became interested in [[neurology]], and worked in Berlin, [[Vienna]], Munich and Paris for a year on a travelling scholarship.

He fought in the First World War in France, firstly as medical officer to the [[Northamptonshire Regiment]], and was one of few survivors from the regiment after the retreat from [[Battle of Mons|Mons]] due to a bout of [[measles]] which kept him from the battle.<ref name=whonamedit /> He was then posted to the [[Leicestershire Regiment]], and was mentioned in despatches for saving a number of soldiers from a gas attack in 1916 by improvising a gas mask made of clothing soaked in urine.<ref name=firkin>Barry G. Firkin, Judith A. Whitworth. ''Dictionary of Medical Eponyms'' Informa Health Care, 2001. ISBN 978-1-85070-333-4</ref> While on leave in 1916 he married Lorraine Bonar; they had two children. He subsequently served as neurological specialist to the 7th General Hospital,<ref name=bmj /> where he advised on management of head injured patients.<ref>Adie WJ, Wagstaffe WW. A note on a series of 656 cases of gunshot wound of the head, with a statistical consideration of the results obtained. ''Medical Research Committee Statistical Reports, no. 1.'' London: Stationery Office, 1918.</ref>

After the war he worked as a medical registrar at [[Charing Cross Hospital]] before working at the [[National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery|National Hospital for Nervous Diseases]], Queens Square, and the [[Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust|Moorfields Eye Hospital]] in London, practising general medicine with neurology as his speciality. He became a [[Membership of the Royal College of Physicians|Member of the Royal College of Physicians]] in 1919. In 1926 he was elected to the [[Royal College of Physicians|Fellowship of the Royal College of Physicians]], and also received the gold medal for his M.D. at Edinburgh.<ref name=bmj />

In 1932 Adie was one of the founders of the '''Association of British Neurologists''', which was formed at a meeting on 28 July at the house of [[Gordon Morgan Holmes|Gordon Holmes]].<ref name=pearce />

Adie was known as an excellent teacher of medicine and a fine diagnostician with extraordinary powers of observation.<ref name=bmj /> His interests also included ornithology, tennis and skiing.<ref name=whonamedit /> At the age of 45 he developed angina, forcing him to retire in 1935. He died on 17 March 1935 from a [[myocardial infarction]] at the age of 48.<ref name=bmj>Obituary of William John Adie. ''Br Med J.'' 1935 March 23;1)3872):624-5</ref>

==Publications==
Adie and his colleague James Collier wrote the neurology chapter in Price's ''Textbook of the Practice of Medicine'' which is considered to be the first account of neurology in a general textbook.<ref name=pearce>{{cite journal |author=Pearce JM |title=William John Adie (1886–1935) |journal=J. Neurol. Neurosurg. Psychiatr. |volume=75 |issue=8 |pages=1111 |year=2004 |month=August |pmid=15258210 |pmc=1739159 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.2003.020321 |url=http://jnnp.bmj.com/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=15258210 |accessdate=8 February 2009}}</ref>

Adie also published articles on pupillary abnormalities,<ref>Adie WJ. Tonic pupils and absent tendon reflexes: a benign disorder sui generis; its complete and incomplete forms. ''Brain'' 1932;55:98–113.</ref> "forced grasping and groping" in frontal lobe disorders,<ref>Adie WJ, Critchley M. Forced grapsing and groping. ''Brain'' 1927;50:142-70.</ref> and narcolepsy.<ref>Adie WJ. Idiopathic narcolepsy: a disease sui generis: with remarks on the mechanism of sleep. ''Brain'' 1926;49:275–306.</ref>

